{{Orphan|date=March 2012}}
'''Hector the Cat''' (also known as '''Hector Cat''', '''Hector the Road Safety Cat''' or simply '''Hector''') is a fictional [[cat]] and [[mascot]] created to aid the teaching of [[Road traffic safety|road safety]] to children in Australia. Educational material relating to the character was developed by the [[Department of Infrastructure and Transport|Australian Department of Transport]] in association with state and territory road authorities.<ref name=maggs>{{cite book|author=Maggs, Alex & Margaret Brown|title=Primary School and Road Safety Curricula: A review of Australian Materials and practices|date=May 1986|publisher=Federal Office of Road Safety|isbn=0642513066 |url=http://www.infrastructure.gov.au/roads/safety/publications/1986/pdf/Child_Edu_5.pdf|accessdate=17 February 2011}}</ref> "Hector's road safety song" became well known in Australia when it was shown as a public service announcement on television. The blue and yellow striped cat first appeared on a school calendar in 1971 with a storyline that he had lost eight of his [[Cat#History and mythology|nine lives]] due to "ignorance of road safety practices".<ref name=maggs/> This was followed by a short instructional film. In subsequent years other characters were introduced in calendars, instructional films, and [[comic book]]s including Millie, his girlfriend (1973), Uncle Tom (1974), Hector and Millie's three kittens (1975) and his space friend Ding Dong (1982).<ref name=maggs/><ref name=NMA>{{cite web|title=Hector's Road Safety Calendar from 1982|work=Search our Collections |publisher=National Museum of Australia|url=http://www.nma.gov.au/collections-search/display?irn=50779|accessdate=17 February 2011}}</ref>
A study in 1978 found that, although children enjoyed the characters and stories, the material had a number of inadequacies. It stressed that road safety research findings and [[child development]] theory would need to be considered for any future development.<ref name=maggs/><ref name=henderson>{{cite web|author=Henderson, Michael |title=Education, publicity and Training in Road Safety: A literature Review - Report No. 22 |date=November 1991 |publisher=Monash University Accident Research Centre |url=http://www.monash.edu.au/muarc/reports/muarc022.pdf |accessdate=17 February 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706114650/http://www.monash.edu.au/muarc/reports/muarc022.pdf |archivedate=6 July 2011 |df= }}</ref>
The character is currently used by the [[Northern Territory]] Department of Transport to promote road awareness to children. The song "Stop, Look, Listen, Think" is featured in his Road Safety Show.<ref name=DOT>{{cite web|title=Hector the Cat |publisher=Department of Transport (Northern Territory) |url=http://transport.nt.gov.au/safety/road-safety/for-children-and-young-people/hector-the-cat |accessdate=25 March 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130427122949/http://www.transport.nt.gov.au/safety/road-safety/for-children-and-young-people/hector-the-cat |archivedate=27 April 2013 |df= }}</ref>
