{{infobox ethnic group| |group=Mal |image= |population=27,893 (est.) |popplace=[[Laos]], [[Thailand]], [[United States]] |langs=[[Mal language|Mal]], [[Lao language|Lao]], [[Thai language|Thai]], others |rels=[[Theravada Buddhism]] |related= }} The '''Mal''' are an ethnic group native to Laos and Thailand. They are one of two sub-groups of the [[Lua people]] (the other one being the [[Phai people|Phai]]).<ref>{{Cite book |author=Joachim Schliesinger |title=Ethnic Groups of Laos, Volume 1: Introduction and Overview |publisher=White Lotus |year=2003 |page=171}}</ref>
==Name Variation== The Mal are also commonly referred to as Madl, Khatin, T'in, Htin, Thin, and Tin.<ref name="Ethnologue report for Laos">[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=LA Ethnologue report for Laos]</ref>
==Language== The Mal speak a language also called [[Mal language|Mal]], which is a [[Khmuic languages|Khmuic language]].<ref name="Ethnologue report for Laos"/> The Khmuic languages are [[Austroasiatic languages|Austroasiatic]].<ref name="Ethnologue report for Laos"/> There is some debate as to whether the Khmuic languages are of the [[Mon–Khmer languages|Mon–Khmer]] branch, but the majority opinion is that they are not.{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}
